frameDefinitions: A trial is a process conducted in a Court before a Judge and (usually) a Jury in which the participants meet in order to decide a Case.
This frame contains words which name permanent fixed structures forming an enclosure and providing protection from the elements.
A Figure is located relative to a Ground location.
Geography as defined by its use.
This frame concerns Communicators communicating with each other with the aid of a Means of communication such as a telephone.

This frame is concerned with the idea that people (Participant_1, Participant_2, or Participants) participate in an organized, rule-governed activity (the Competition) in order to achieve some advantageous outcome (often the Prize).
frameExamples: The baroque <t>church</t>, built in 1635, has a very rich interior
You must land in the next <t><fex name='Locale'>airfield</fex></t>, as this one is currently having difficulties.
listRoleDefinitions: The legal label for the crime that the <fen>Defendant</fen> is accused of.
The specific room where the participants in a Trial meet.

The individual or group which is responsible for promoting the welfare of the  <fen>Defendant</fen> during a Trial, usually involving the contention that the <fen>Defendant</fen> is innocent of the <fen>Charges</fen>.
The group of individuals who observe the Trial and ultimately attempt to come to a verdict.
The individual or group responsible for promoting the interests of the state in the Trial, prototypically including presenting arguments for the guilt of the <fen>Defendant</fen>.
The person charged with an offence.
The official who directs and presides over the Trial.
The <fen>Case</fen> which a Trial is convened to decide.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the trial occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the trial occurs.
The entity built by the <fen>Builder</fen> which has some <fen>Function</fen>.
The building's location.
The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The <fen>Figures</fen> are items which mutually serve to identify the location of the other items.
The region within which a <fen>Figure</fen> might be found.  This role is exclusive of <fen>Figure</fen>, and is a reconstrual that is not possible with verb lexical units.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
A stable bounded area.  It is typically the designation of the nouns of Locale-derived frames.
The activity that is carried out in the <fen>Locale</fen>.

This role is the person who uses the <fen>Means</fen> of communication to deliver the <fen>Message</fen> to the Addressee. The Speaker is normally expressed as the External Argument of target verbs, or as the Genitive modifier of  nouns.

<fen>Addressee</fen> is the person to whom the <fen>Message</fen> is communicated. When this role is expressed, it often appears in a prepositional phrase introduced by to, or as the direct object, or as the first object in a double object construction.
This role identifies the content that the <fen>Communicator</fen> communicates to the <fen>Addressee</fen>. It can be expressed as a clause or as a noun phrase.
<fen>Topic</fen> is the subject matter to which the <fen>Message</fen> pertains. It is typically expressed as a PP Complement headed by about.

This Frame Element refers to the Instrument of Communication that is used by the <fen>Communicator</fen> (and <fen>Addressee</fen>). Each LU in this frame incorporates the <fen>Means</fen> frame element.
This role identifies the first (or only) participant in a competition.
This role identifies the second participant in a competition.
This role is used for plural NP participants in a competition.
This role is used for the name of the competition.
The period of time when the <fen>Competition</fen> occurs.

Where the event takes place. 
A constituent tagged as <fen>Place</fen> may require annotation on a secondary FE-layer.
listRoleExamples: <fex><t>Next to</t> the kitchen</fex> is the best place to locate your garage .
There used to be a carnival every summer in that <fex><t>city</t></fex>.
The Campus <fex>Microscopy and Imaging</fex> Facility (CMIF) serves a wide range of faculty staff and students of The Ohio State University .
<fex>The President</fex> cabled his assistant to cancel all of his appointments.
The President cabled <fex>his assistant</fex> to cancel all other engagements.
First layer: John's first competition <fex>at Wimbledon</fex> astonished the crowd.

sourceCandidateSpans.text: the World Golf Hall of Fame
